body:
I tracked the problem down to an interaction with `maxStateOnlySize`. A high value (~195) does not trigger the bug. A medium value seems to trigger it less. And 1 triggers it very quickly. 0 doesn't have any issue.

I also know that the streamableBytes on many streams is incorrectly 0. I think this was caused by child/pseudoTimeQueue tree corruption, because it seems there were large trees that weren't descendant from the connection.

It seems the problem is due to a bug in updateDependencyTree, where if it doesn't find the parent it creates new State for it, but it doesn't give that State a parent. This seems to fix it (more testing needed):
```java
@@ -229,6 +229,10 @@ public final class WeightedFairQueueByteDistributor implements StreamByteDistrib
         State newParent = state(parentStreamId);
         if (newParent == null) {
             // If there is no State object that means there is no Http2Stream object and we would have to keep the
             // State object in the stateOnlyMap and stateOnlyRemovalQueue. However if maxStateOnlySize is 0 this means
             // stateOnlyMap and stateOnlyRemovalQueue are empty collections and cannot be modified so we drop the State.
             if (maxStateOnlySize == 0) {
                 return;
             }
             newParent = new State(parentStreamId);
             stateOnlyRemovalQueue.add(newParent);
             stateOnlyMap.put(parentStreamId, newParent);
+            // Only the stream which was just added will change parents. So we only need an array of size 1.
+            List<ParentChangedEvent> events = new ArrayList<ParentChangedEvent>(1);
+            connectionState.takeChild(newParent, false, events);
+            notifyParentChanged(events);
         }
```

Although I'm becoming more familiar with the code, I am not fully up-to-speed. I'll see if I can turn this into a PR.
